article.description: Dionnah Jackson had 23 points and eight assists to lead  Oklahoma (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today, No. 22 AP) to an 84-62 season-opening victory over Southeast Missouri State on Friday night.
article.headline: Jackson paces Sooners with 23 points
article.linkText: Oklahoma uses late run to pull away from SEMO
article.story:
NORMAN, Okla. (AP) -- Oklahoma turned the ball over and missed
free throws more than coach Sherri Coale would've liked, but Coale
saw more good than bad in the Sooners' season-opening victory.

Dionnah Jackson scored 23 points and Krista Sanchez added 17 as
the Sooners beat Southeast Missouri State 84-62 Friday night.

"We did some really good things with the basketball," Coale
said. "We had 25 assists and that's a smart offensive game. I know
we turned it over 17 times and that's a few too many.

"With the way they play though, that number's not that bad."

SE Missouri State (0-1) trailed by as much as nine twice in the
first half, but managed to go into half time tied with Oklahoma
(1-0) at 38-38. But a 10-0 run, sparked by Leah Rush's jumper at
12:36, put Oklahoma ahead for good.

Coale credited Lauren Shoush, who had eight rebounds, a
3-pointer and three rebounds in the second half.

"She was the difference," Coale said. "Her minutes in the
first half were OK, but she didn't impact the game. The play of the
game was when she flew in and tipped the offensive board and saved
it. Suddenly the crowd got involved in the game and everyone on the
floor felt alive."

Shoush finished with 6 points and 10 rebounds.

It was Shoush's 3-point at 15:41 left in the game that put
Oklahoma ahead 48-41, and a free throw about a minute later gave
the Sooners a 49-42 lead.

After a free throw by Sanchez, Dionnah Jackson fouled and
Natalie Purcell hit both free throws to cut the advantage to 50-44.
A layup by Tatiana Conceicao, SE Missouri State's leading scorer,
narrowed the score to 50-46, but two turnovers and a foul sealed
the game.

"Their defense was really intense, but we got a lot of
backdoors and really kept our composure," Sanchez said.

"... I think it's just a matter of playing your game as opposed
to theirs."

Conceicao led all scorers with 26 points for Southeast Missouri
State, and Purcell added 15.

The Sooners faltered in 3-point range, hitting only 7-of-18
(33.3 percent), but went 32-of-65 (49.2 percent) from the field for
the game.

Southeast Missouri State shot 44.7 percent from the field.
